==English==

===Etymology===
The English word sin derives from Old English ''synn''. The same root appears in several other Germanic languages, e.g., Old Norse ''synd'', or German ''[[Sünde]]''. The word may derive, ultimately, from *es-, one of the Indo-European roots that meant "to be," and is a present participle, "being." Latin, also has an old present participle of ''[[esse]]'' in the word ''sons'', ''sont-'', which came to mean "guilty" in Latin. The root meaning would appear to be, "it is true;" that is, "the charge has been proven." The Greek word {{IPAchar|[[αμαρτία|ἁμαρτία]]}} (''hamartia'') is often translated as sin in the New Testament; it means "to miss the mark" or "to miss the target.

